While direct evidence linking biofeedback specifically to enhanced *sport* performance is limited, several studies show improvements in neuromuscular function—including quadriceps strength, balance, and gait—which are foundational elements of athletic ability. Moreover, biofeedback enables athletes to develop greater awareness and voluntary control over physiologic processes like muscle activation and stress response, potentially leading to optimized performance under pressure. Given the established benefit in post-surgical rehabilitation and neuromotor retraining, extending these gains to elite sport settings is plausible.

